AT 21:45 ON NOV. 4TH THE WAREHOUSE STAFF WAS LOADING A 143 LOT OF CORROSIVE MATERIAL, WHILE LOADING ONE OF THE JERRICANS WAS DROPPED ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  UPON IMPACT THE CLOSURE OF THE JERRICAN CAME OFF AND THE CONTENTS SPILLED ONTO THE WAREHOUSE FLOOR.  THE DFW AIRPORT FIRE DEPT WAS CALLED, THEY EVACUATED THE FACILITY AS A PRECAUTIONARY MEASURE UNTIL A DGR CLEAN UP COMPANY COULD BE CALLED.  NO STAFF WERE INJURED AND THE SPILL WAS PROPERLY CLEANED UP.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: UNIT TRAVELING NORTH BOUND ON I-71 WHEN DRIVER APPARENTLY FELL ASLEEP AND DRIFTED INTO GUARDRAIL ON RIGHT SIDE OF NORTH BOUND LANES, CONTACT WITH GUARD RAIL STARTLED DRIVER AND WHEN HE ATTEMPTED TO RECOVER THE UNIT, IT OVERTURNED ONTO IT'S SIDE ON THE HIGHWAY AND SLID OFF INTO THE MEDIAN BETWEEN THE PAVED ROADWAYS.  AS A RESULT OF THE IMPACT, THERE APPEARS TO BE A CRACK IN A WELD ON THE TOP OF THE LADDER ON THE SIDE OF THE CARGO TANK AND PRODUCT WAS DRIPPING FROM THIS AREA.  ESTIMATE ONLY OF LOST MATERIAL IS UP TO 20 GALLONS, WEIGHTS HAVE NOT BEEN COLLECTED TO CONFIRM THIS AS OF THIS WRITING.  PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO A SERVICEABLE UNIT USING A DIAPHRAM PUMP AND COMPRESSOR.  ENVIRONMENTAL CONTRACTORS HAVE BEEN ASSIGNED TO PERFORM ALL NECESSARY REMEDIATION AT THE SCENE OF THIS ACCIDENT.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE ON THE DOCK, ONE LEAKING FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS DISCOVERED. APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF FREE PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO HEAVY FREIGHT BEING LOADED ON TOP OF THE METAL PAIL, CAUSING IT TO BE CRUSHED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL C PROTECTION AND AMPHOMAG. THE CLEANUP MATERIALS AND AFFECTED DUNNAGE WERE PLACED INTO A TWENTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM. THE LEAKING FIVE GALLON METAL PAIL WAS PLACED INTO A THIRTY GALLON PLASTIC RECOVERY DRUM. BOTH DRUMS WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL AWAITING DISPOSITION. THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT WAS FORWARDED TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Inadequate Blocking and Bracing
column168: DRIVER NOTICED UPON ARRIVAL AT CONSIGNEE THAT 1 55 GAL. DRUM HAD FELL OVER ONTO ANOTHER DRUM CAUSED AN INDENTATION AND SMALL LEAK UP AROUND THE TOP LIP OF THE DRUM. CLEAN-UP WAS SUPERVISED PER WALTER WATSON AT NORTH AMERICAN COMPOSITE. FLOOR-DRY ABSORBANT WAS DISPERSED ON FLOOR AND WAS THEN SHOVELED INTO A DISPOSAL CONTAINER. DRIVER THEN WASHED OUT TRAILER.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: UPON ARRIVAL AT THE NEWARK, NJ FACILITY ONE DRUM WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING. THE DRUM HAD BEEN SHIPPED WITH A SCREW EMBEDDED IN THE SIDE. THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS CLEANED UP USING A CLAY ABSORBENT. THE DAMAGED DRUM WAS OVERPACKED INTO A SALVAGE CONTAINER. ALL OF THE FREIGHT WAS SHIPPED TO AND ACCEPTED BY THE CONSIGNEE.

AN UNKNOWN ALKALINE CLEANER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM AN INBOUND TRAILER AT THE NORTH OXFORD, MA FACILITY. THE LIQUID WAS ON THE DOCK AND IN THE PARKING LOT. THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP USING A CLAY ABSORBENT AND NEUTRALIZER, BY A THIRD PARTY CONTRACTOR. THE SPILL CLEAN UP MATERIAL WAS PACKED INTO A STEEL DRUM AND PLACED IN THE HAZARDOUS WASTE STORAGE AREA FOR DISPOSAL BY AN OUTSIDE VENDOR.

column62: Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails)
column168: DURING OFF-LOADING AT THE TERMINAL, IT WAS OBSERVED THAT FREE LIQUID WAS ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER. ONE DRUM WAS OBSERVED TO BE LEAKING. THE FACILITY CONTACTED A LOCAL RESPONSE AGENCY DUE TO ITS HAZARDOUS NATURE. THE RESPONSE COMPANY CLEANED THE FREE LIQUID, NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID, AND OVERPACKED THE DRUM. THE DRUM WAS HELD FROM THE SHIPMENT AT THE TERMINAL. THE DRUM WILL BE SENT OUT FOR HAZARDOUS WASTE DISPOSAL AS AUTHORIZED BY THE SHIPPER. THE LOADER OF THIS MATERIAL WAS COUNSELED ON PROPER TRAILER INSPECTION PRIOR TO LOADING TO ENSURE THAT THE FLOORS ARE CLEAN AND FREE OF MATERIAL POSSIBLY PUNCTURING CONTAINERS.
WHILE DRIVER BILL VICK WAS MOVING HIS FREIGHT HE PUNCTURED THE DRUM WITH BLADE OF FORK LIFT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: BNSF SWITCH CREW REPORTED GATX 16459 IN RAIL YARD WITH PRODUCT SPILLAGE FROM MANWAY COVER. BNSF RESPONDER FOUND MANWAY BOLTS SECURE BUT MANWAY GASKET MISALIGNED WITH HALF OF THE GASKET HANGING DOWN INTO MANWAY NOZZLE. ON 11/07, SHIPPER CONTRACTOR (RESCAR) REPLACED GASKET, INSTALLING A VITON GASKET & RESECURED MANWAY COVER. ANOTHER CONTRACTOR NEUTRALIZED SPILLED PRODUCT ON TANK SHELL.

column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Water Damage; Defective Component or Device; Freezing
column168: BNSF TRAIN CREW IN RAIL YARD REPORTED RECENTLY ARRIVED BN 974399 LEAKING PRODUCT FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET AREA. CONTAINMENT RECEPTACLE WAS PLACED UNDER TANK CAR. BNSF & LOCAL F.D. RESPONDERS WERE ABLE TO STOP LEAK BY CLOSING THE TOBOV (TOP OPERATED BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE) OPERATING ROD 3 FULL TURNS. THE PACKING GLAND NUT AROUND OPERATING ROD WAS ALSO TIGHTENED. A BUILD-UP OF ICE IN TOBOV PREVENTED PRIOR FULL CLOSURE. AN ESTIMATED 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT RELEASED TO THIS POINT. THE NEXT MORNING, ADDITIONAL PRODUCT SPILLAGE NOTICED UNDER BN 974399. APPARENTLY, WATER IN THE BOTTOM T-PIPE UNLOADING FITTINGS FROZE OVER NIGHT, EXPANDED & CRACKED THE PIPE AROUND THE CAM-LOCK QUICK CONNECT DEVICE. CRACK ALLOWED ADDITIONAL PRODUCT IN THE UNLOADING PIPES (FROM OPEN TOBOV) TO LEAK OUT WHEN TEMPERATURES WARMED. BNSF RESPONDERS FLANGED OFF CONNECTION & DRAINED UNLOADING PIPES TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER PRODUCT RELEASE FROM THIS AREA. TANK CAR WAS UNLOADED & SENT TO REPAIR FACILITY. SPILLED PRODUCT WAS REMEDIATED.

ON NOVEMBER 2, 2003, AN EMPLOYEE AT THE CSXT YARD IN ERWIN, TN OBSERVED CHVX 280009 DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND LEAK CONTAINED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER DISPATCHED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO THE YARD.  UPON ARRIVAL, CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL FOUND THE CAR LEAKING FROM UNDER THE JACKET AT AN UNKNOWN LOCATION.  APPROXIMATELY ONE QUART OF PRODUCT HAD BEEN CAPTURED IN A BUCKET.  A RESIDUE XYLENE TANK CAR (CHVX 280120) WAS LOCATED IN THE YARD AND CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL TRANSFERRED THE CONTENTS OF CHVX 280009 INTO THE RESIDUE CAR.  AFTER THE PRODUCT TRANSFER, CONTRACTOR PERSONNEL CLEANED AND PURGED CHVX 280009, AND THE CAR WAS RELEASED TO A CAR FACILITY FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.

column168: (A) ON NOVEMBER 5, 2003, CSX WAS NOTIFIED THAT TRAIN Q64704 WAS OBSERVED PASSING THROUGH MURFREESBORO, TN WITH A NOTICEABLE ODOR. ON NOVEMBER 13, 2003 AT APP. 1800 HR., OUR DRIVER WAS PUMPING OFF A LOAD OF NH 3 AT FARMERS AG SERVICE GIFFORD, IL.  HE ARRIVED AT APP. 1740 HR, HE HOOKED UP THE HOSES AND PREPARED TO START TO PUMP OFF.  AT APP. 1800 HR, HE TURNED ON THE PUMP TO START THE PUMPING ACTION, WHEN HE HEARD A BOOM.  HE IMMEDIATELY TRIED TO GET TO THE EMERGENCY SHUTOFF VALVE, BUT WAS UNABLE TO GET THERE.  FARMERS AG SERVICE EMPLOYEE CALLED 911 AND THE FIRE DEPARTMENT ALONG WITH THE EMERGENCY PERSONAL FROM THE COUNTY CAME.  UPON THEIR ARRIVAL, THEY SHUT OFF THE TRUCK AND PULL THE EMERGENCY VALVE ON THE CARGO TRAILER, WHICH SHUT EVERYTHING OFF.  D & B TRUCKING HAS SINCE BOUGHT FROM ROCKET SUPPLY, IN ROBERTS, IL A SMART HOSE, WHICH SHOULD ELIMINATE THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

column168: WHEN UNLOADING AT OUR PARSONS DOCK, IT WAS NOTICED THAT THE CAP ON TOP WAS CRACKED CAUSING A VERY SMALL LEAK.  WE CONTACTED SHIPPER AND THEY GAVE US A REPLACEMENT CAP TO PUT ON.  IT WAS DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE AND THEY ACCEPTED THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT.

PACKAGE WAS PUNCTURED BY FORK BEFORE IT WAS SHRINK WRAPPED.  IT WAS SHIPPED TO FED EX FREIGHT DOCK.  NOTICED SPILL WHEN UNLOADED.  CLEANED UP SPILL AND PUT IN PLASTIC BAG.  NOTIFIED SHIPPER ABOUT CHECKING FREIGHT BEFORE SHRINK WRAP IS APPLIED.

OUR DRIVER, WHILE UNLOADING HIS TRAILER, MOVED THE TRUCK FORWARD TO ENABLE HIS HOSE TO REACH ANOTHER TANK.  THE CONNECTED HOSE WAS NOT LONG ENOUGH AND SPLIT CAUSING THE SPILL.  ONCE WE WERE NOTIFIED, WE DISPATCHED OUR INITIAL RESPONSE CLEAN-UP CREW AND EQUIPMENT TO THE SCENE ALONG WITH A MEMBER OF OUR SPILL RESPONSE MANAGEMENT TEAM.  THEY WERE ABLE TO COMPLETE CLEAN-UP OF THE SIGHT.  THE DRIVER AS A MEMBER OF THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION TEAM PARTICIPATED IN THE INVESTIGATION AND AGREED WITH THE TEAMS' CONCLUSION AND SOLUTIONS.  THE RESULTS OF THE INCIDENT INVESTIGATION WILL BE FORWARDED TO ALL DRIVERS IN THE COMPANY.

DRIVER WAS STARTING TO PUMP DIESEL FUEL INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK. CUSTOMER HAD NO OPENED TO VALVE.  THIS CAUSE PRESSURE ON THE FITTING WHICH FAILED.  SMALL AMOUNT OF DIESEL SPILLED BUT WAS CLEANED UP BY UPS AND DRIVER WITH USE OF ABSORBENTS.  SOUTHERN WASTE SERVICES WAS CALLED TO COMPLETE CLEAN UP AND REMOVED ABSORBENTS.

DRUMS WERE BEING CROSSLOADED FROM A FLAT BED TO A VAN.  ONE DRUM WAS PUNCTURED AND KNOCKED OVER. AFTER THIS HAPPENED OTHER DRUMS WERE CHECKED AND ONE OTHER DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE PUNCTURED.  BOTH DRUMS WERE PUT INTO OVERPACK DRUMS ALONG WITH SPILLED PRODUCT ABSORBED UP WITH FLOOR DRY & OTHER MATERIALS.  MORE FORKLIFT TRAINING HAS BEEN GIVEN TO ALL EMPLOYEES ON SITE WHO USE FORKLIFTS.
FREIGHT WAS LOADED WITHOUT PROPER DUNNAGE PROTECTING IT FROM OTHER SHIPMENTS ALLOWING IT TO BE PUNCTURED.
THE CAP ON THE 5 GALLON PAIL CAME OFF AND DURING TRANSIT LIQUID SLOSHED OUT.

column62: Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: FOUND SPILL ON THE DOCK WHEN I GOT TO WORK.  AROUND 1200 NOON, I HAD TO LOCATE A PKG ON THE DOCK AND THAT IS WHEN I BECAME AWARE OF THE SPILL.  I CALLED THE HAZ HOTLINE FOR INSTRUCTIONS.  THEY SENT A SPILL TEAM TO OUR LOCATION AND THE SPILL WAS CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF ON SITE.  ONE BOTTLE WAS SAVED AND PACKED ACCORDINGLY.  ANY OTHER QUESTIONS PLEASE CALL MY CELL PHONE AT 240 832 1970.  THANKS ERNIE.

column42: PAINT RELATED MATERIAL INCLUDING PAINT THINNING, DRYING, REMOVING, OR REDUCING COMPOUND
column168: DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO UNLOAD A TRAILER WITH A FORK LIFT.  A SHIPMENT OF FIVE 55 GALLON DRUMS WAS LOADED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER IN FRONT OF SOME SKIDS.  THE DRIVER ENTERED THE TRAILER TO PK/UP A SKID, DIDN'T REALIZE THAT HIS FORKS WERE OUT OF THE BACK OF THE SKID AND STRUCK ONE OF THE DRUMS.   THIS CAUSES A SMALL PUNCTURE NEAR THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  WE TURNED THE DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLAGE OF PRODUCT.  WE THEN PLACED THE DRUM IN AN OVERPACK SALVAGE DRUM AND PLACED IT IN OUR OS&D AREA.

OUR VEHICLE WAS FUELING EQUIPMENT AT OUR JOB SITE DRIVER WAS DISTRACTED AND AUTOMATIC SHUTOFF VALVE FAILED ON NOZZLE, ALLOWING 1 TO 2 GALLONS TO SPILL. FUEL ENTERED WATERWAY, AND WAS CONTAINED AND REMOVED USING BOOMS.  DRIVER AND EMPLOYEES ASSISTED CERTIFIED TECH FROM GLOVER OIL COMPANY.  BOOMS HAVE BEEN PROPERLY DISPOSED OF WITH SPACE COAST OIL RECYCLING.

column168: RECEIVER CLOSED HIS VALVES AND TOLD DRIVER TO UNHOOK.  WHEN HE DID, THE REMAINING PRODUCT STILL IN HOSE SPRAYED ONTO CONCRETE WALL.  SHIPPER CLEANED CONCRETE WALL AND FLOOR.  SOME PRODUCT SPRAYED ON DRIVER'S RUBBER SUIT, BUT HE WAS NOT INJURED.

column168: DRUM WAS PUNCTURED BY A FORKLIFT DURING THE UNLOADING OF THE TRAILER.  DSR WAS UNLOADING AND SPEARED THE DRUM ABOUT 2" UP FROM THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM. DSR WAS INSTRUCTED TO USE BARREL TRUCK INSTEAD OF TOW MOTOR TO MOVE DRUMS. ABOUT 2 GALLONS OF ACETONE WAS RELEASED ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  THE DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY LAID ON ITS SIDE SO THE PUNCTURE WAS FACE UP.  DRUM WAS THEN PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  ABSORBENT WAS USED TO SOAK UP THE SPILLED ACETONE AND WAS PLACED IN A 35 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM.
DRUM WAS STAGED ON DOCK FOR LOADING.  FORKLIFT PUNCTURED DRUM NEAR BOTTOM EDGE.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE UNLOADING AT THE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. FACILITY A LEAK WAS DISCOVERED IN THE TRAILER. UPON INSPECTION, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT ONE CARTON, CONTAINING FOUR (4) ONE LITER GLASS BOTTLE, HAD BEEN CRUSHED BY A PALLET DUE TO THE LOAD SHIFTING IN TRANSIT. ONE (1) ONE LITER GLASS BOTTLE HAD BEEN DAMAGED. TERMINAL PERSONNEL PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING LEVEL D EQUIPMENT. ABSORBENT MATERIAL WAS APPLIED TO THE FREE LIQUID INSIDE THE TRAILER. CLEANUP MATERIALS WERE PLACED INTO ONE (1) THIRTY GALLON FIBER RECOVERY DRUM ALONG WITH THE DAMAGED FREIGHT AND CONTAINED  CARDBOARD. THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED. MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ONE (1) THIRTY-GALLON RECOVERY DRUM WILL BE HELD AT THE TERMINAL PENDING DISPOSAL.

ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE LOADING, ONE, ONE HUNDRED AND THIRTY-FIVE POUND STEEL CYLINDER WAS DROPPED DURING HANDLING. APPROXIMATELY TWENTY POUNDS OF FREE PRODUCT WERE RELEASED AND DISSIPATED. THE RELEASE WAS DUE TO A MISSING SAFETY CAP ON THE RELEASE VALVE. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM EVACUATED THE DOCK. THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT AND MATHESON TRI-GAS, INC. RESPONDED TO THE TERMINAL. THE HOUSTON FIRE DEPARTMENT SHUT OFF THE VALVE ON THE LEAKING CYLINDER. MATHESON TRI-GAS, INC. PLACED A SAFETY CAP ON THE VALVE.THE CYLINDER WAS FORWARDED WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. THREE ROADWAY EXPRESS, INC. EMPLOYEES WERE EXPOSED TO THE FREE PRODUCT AND TRANSPORTED TO LBJ HOSPITAL IN HOUSTON, TEXAS, WHERE THEY WERE EVALUATED AND RELEASED. A FOURTH EMPLOYEE FELT UNCOMFORTABLE REMAINING AT THE TERMINAL AND LEFT FOR THE DAY. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED. ALL FEDERAL, STATE, AND LOCAL REGULATORY AUTHORITIES WERE NOTIFIED.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. THE TERMINAL HAZMAT TEAM PERFORMED THE CLEANUP USING GLOVES, ABSORBENT PADS AND WATER. THE DRUM WAS CLEANED, RECOUPED AND FORWARDED  WITH THE REMAINDER OF THE SHIPMENT TO THE CONSIGNEE. NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES WERE REPORTED. THE MSDS WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED.

LIQUID VALVE CLOSURE CAP WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT, UTLX 80024, NOVEMBER 7, 2003, SOUTH JERSEY DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 0730 HOURS, FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 7, 2003, AT STONEY CREEK YARD IN TRAINER, PA, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR NOTED FROST ON OPERATING VALVE CABINET AND VAPOR VENTING FROM TANK CAR UTLX 80024, CONTAINING ETHYLENE REFRIGERATED LIQUID.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  REPRESENTATIVES FROM SUNOCO AND UNION TANK CAR CO. ARRIVED AND FOUND THAT MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS LEAKING BY THE CLOSED LIQUID VALVE; AND, THE LIQUID VALVE CLOSURE CAP WAS NOT TOOL TIGHT.  CAP TIGHTENED TO TEMPORARILY SECURE LEAK, CAR CUT OUT OF TRAIN AND IMMEDIATELY DELIVERED BACK TO SUNOCO'S ETHYLENE LOADING RACK.  CAR CONTENTS UNLOADED INTO TANK CAR SUNX 90008 AT PLANT (AS REPORTED BY SUNOCO).  CAR WILL BE PURGED SO THAT CAN BE HOME SHOPPED FOR REPAIRS.

D. CAMERON LEFT JCI WITH A LOAD OF SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE GOING TO MANCHESTER WASTE WATER.  HE WAS A QUARTER OF A MIKE FROM JCI WHEN A LOCAL FIRE FIGHTER PULLED DOUG OVER.  THE FIRE FIGHTERS NOTED MATERIAL WAS COMING OUT OF THE TOP OF THE TRAILER.  DOUG CALLED SHI DISPATCH AND SAID AN AIR VALVE WAS CRACKED OPEN AND THAT IS WHERE THE PRODUCT CAME FROM.  APPROXIMATELY LESS THAN A GALLON SPILLED FROM THE VALVE WHICH IS UNDER THE REPORTABLE QUANTITY OF 100 POUNDS.  THE MERRIMACK FIRE DEPARTMENT HOSED THE TRAILER DOWN WITH WATER TO DILUTE THE SODIUM HYPOCHLORITE RESIDUE ON THE TRAILER.  NH DOT CONDUCTED AN INSPECTION OF THE TRUCK/TRAILER AND FOUND A TAIL LIGHT OUT THAT HAD BEEN WORKING AND THE VIK INSPECTIONS EXPIRED.  DOUG CAMERON/ BILL KUVAJA BOTH CALLED JCI TO NOTIFY THEM OF THE SITUATION.  THE TRAILER WAS BROUGHT BACK TO JCI.  A DOT DVE REPORT WAS ISSUED FOR SPILLING MATERIAL, A VENT LEFT OPEN, RIGHT REAR DIRECTIONAL NOT OPERATING, AND TANK NOT MARKED WITH PROPER VIK TEST DATES.  DOT OUT OF SERVICES WERE ISSUED FOR THE VENT BEING OPEN AND THE RIGHT REAR DIRECTIONAL NOT OPERATING.  TWO FINES FOR $72.00 EACH WERE ISSUED FOR SPILLING MATERIAL AND FAILURE TO MARK THE TANK WITH THE PROPER VIK TEST DATES.

column168: A FORKLIFT OPERATOR WAS UNLOADING EMPTY INTERMEDIATE BULK CONTAINERS (TOTES) FROM A VAN TRAILER AT DOCK 41.  THE LAST TWO TOTES WERE DOUBLE STACKED AGAINST SOME DRUMS OF WASTE MATERIAL BEING TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER FACILITY.  THESE TOTES WERE LOADED SUCH THAT THEIR SHORT SIDE FACED THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  THE OPERATOR WAS UNAWARE OF THIS WHEN HE SLID THE TRUCK FORKS INTO THE BOTTOM TOTE PALLET, NOR COULD HE SEE WHAT WAS LOADED BEHIND, AND SPEARED THE SUBJECT DRUM, LEAVING A 11/2" BY 4" GASH, APPROXIMATELY 1" FROM THE BOTTOM.  UNAWARE OF THE DAMAGE AT THIS POINT, HE BACKED OUT OF THE TRAILER, AND STORED THE TOTES ON THE DOCK.  UPON RETURNING TO THE TRAILER 20 TO 30 SECONDS LATER, APPROXIMATELY 50 GALLONS OF THE DRUMS CONTENTS HAD SPILLED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, AND OUT OF THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  DEFENSE MEASURES WERE TAKEN TO CONTAIN THE RELEASE AND MITIGATE HAZARDS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS ABSORBED, CONTAINERIZED AND IDENTIFIED FOR SUBSEQUENT DISPOSAL.  THE DRUM AND THE REMAINDER OF ITS CONTENTS WERE TRANSFERRED TO A SALVAGE DRUM, WHICH WAS RELABELED AND REMARKED, AND DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE.  UPON REVIEW OF THE INCIDENT, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE CAUSE OF THE RELEASE WAS OPERATOR ERROR.  OPERATOR TRAINING HAD BEEN MODIFIED AND REINFORCED.  OPERATORS ARE NOW REQUIRED TO DRAG PALLETIZED GOODS AWAY FROM OTHER LADING TO THE REAR, PRIOR TO RUNNING TRUCK FORKS ALL THE WAY THROUGH PALLETS.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED, GATX 22428, NOVEMBER 18, 2003, NORTH EAST DIVISION AT APPROXIMATELY 1915 HOURS, TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 18, 2003, AT PORT READING YARD, IN PORT READING, NEW JERSEY, A CONRAIL BRAKEMAN NOTICED PRODUCT LEAKING AT A STEADY STREAM FROM THE BOTTOM OF TANK CAR GATX 22482 CONTAINING SODIUM HYDROXIDE, SOLUTION.  APPROPRIATE NOTIFICATION MADE.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM FMC ARRIVED AT THE SITE, EXAMINED THE TANK CAR AND DETERMINED THAT THE TOP OPERATING BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE WAS NOT CLOSED.  ADDITIONALLY, THE PACKING GLAND NUT FOR THE VALVE OPERATING STEM ON TOP OF THE CAR WAS NOT EVEN HAND TIGHT; CLOSURE FLANGE WITH CLOSURE PLUG NOT SECURED TO MOUNTING FLANGE AND NOZZLE OF BOTTOM OUTLET.  A REPRESENTATIVE FROM FMC SECURED THE LEAKING BY CLOSING THE VALVE AND TIGHTENING THE PACKING GLAND NUT ON THE VALVE STEM.  REACT SECURED THE REMAINING FITTINGS ON THE TANK CAR.  REACT REMEDIATED THE TANK CAR AND SPILLED AREA.

1 SMALL BOX CONTAINING 4, 1 GALLON JUGS WAS PLACED ON THE FLOOR OF THE TRAILER BETWEEN 2 PALLETS. DURING TRANSIT FROM SHIPPER TO THE DOCK THE PALLETS SHIFTED CRUSHING THE CARTON AND THE PRODUCT INSIDE

DRIVER ARRIVED AT CONSIGNEE AND DURING THE PROCESS OF OBTAINING A PRODUCT SAMPLE FROM CARGO TANK, TIPPED THE SAMPLE DIPPER OVER ALLOWING THE 2 QUART CONTENTS TO SPILL ONTO THE SIDE OF THE TRAILER AND TO THE GROUND. THE CUSTOMER WASHED THE ACIDE DOWN FROM THE TRAILER AND TO THEIR COLLECTION PIT TO BE HANDLED WITH OTHER PLANT WASTE. DRIVER CAUTIONED TO PROCESS FOR HANDLING SAMPLE COLLECTION EQUIPMENT.

DURING THE UNLOADING OF THIS LOAD, A LEAK DEVELOPED IN THE CONSIGNEE'S FITTING, BUCKETS WERE USED TO COLLECT THE LEAKAGE AND THE LOAD WAS COMPLETELY TRANSFERRED WITH A TOTAL LOSS OF APPROXIMATELY 10 GALLONS WHICH WAS CAPTURED IN THE BUCKETS. CONSIGNEE DISPOSED OF SPILLED MATERIAL. CONSIGNEE HAD TO REPLACE A GASKET IN THEIR FITTING TO REMEDY THIS PROBLEM.

RECEIVED WITH LOOSE BUNG FROM TRAILER # 313-5387 OUT OF UIV. REATTACHED BUNG WITH PROPER SEAL, WRAPPED IN PLASTIC FILM TO GUARANTEE NON LEAKAGE. CONTACTED SAFETY DEPT. IN THE FUTURE PLEASE CHECK ALL HAZMAT SHIPMENTS TO ASSURE THEY ARE SECURE AND READY FOR TRANSPORT.

column168: MASTER OF SL FLORIDA, DON DAVIS NOTIFIED ME BY TELEX ON 11/17/03 THAT CONTAINER MAEU6096922, 40FT STEEL CONTAINER HAD LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE NOS (MALATHION 97%), CLASS 9, UN 3082, PGIII, BRAND NAME FYFANON. CONTAINER CONTAINED 20 IBC'S, 260 GALLONS PER IBC. HE ADVISED SPILL WAS CONTAINED AND NONE HAD SPILLED OVER THE SHIP INTO WATER. IN HIS TELEX HE NOTIFIED CHEMTREC. I THEN BEGAN MAKING PLANS AND NOTIFICATIONS TO HANDLE UPON ARRIVAL OF VESSEL AT APM TERMINALS BARBOURS CUT. I NOTIFIED CORPORATE HAZMAT KEVIN O' BRIEN ON 11/17/03. I CONTACTED CHEMTREC REQUESTING A CHEMINOVA SEND ME A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET AND SENT A TELEX TO CUSTOMER SERVICE TO ALSO MAKE CONTACT TO SHIPPER. MIKE MURPHY AT CHENTRECT PROVIDE REPORT NUMBER 11-17-2003-031. I RECEIVED A CALL FROM ALLEN VAN WAGGONER OF CHEMIINOVA. HE ADVISED TO GO TO WEBSITE WWW.CHEMINOVA.US.COM TO RETRIEVE MSDS INFORMATION. I NOTIFIED HULCHER EMERGENCY RESPONSE VENDOR AND PUT THEM ON NOTICE OF NEEDED RESPONSE UPON VESSEL ARRIVAL ON 11/19/03. I RECEIVED A CALL FROM BOB BRYANT REPRESENTATIVE FOR CONSIGNEE SCHIRM USA P O BOX 237, ENNIS TX 75120, PHONE 972-875-8456. I REQUESTED THEY BRING A EMPTY IBC, LABELS, AND PLACARDS IN EVENT ANY MATERIAL HAS TO BE TRANSFERRED. MR. BRYANT AND HIS COLLEAGUE ARRIVED ON 11/18/03 WITH IBC. I MET WITH THEM TO DISCUSS OUR PLAN FOR 11/19/03. I NOTIFIED USCG BY FAX ADVISING ALL HAZARDOUS INFORMATION, PLANS FOR HANDLING UPON ARRIVAL. ON 11/18/03 I CALLED TO CONFIRM USCG RECEIVED THE FAX I SPOKE WITH OFFICER PREIFER. ON 11/18/03 I NOTIFIED NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER SPOKE WITH OFFICER THREATT, ASSIGNED REPORT NUMBER 705694. SHORTLY AFTER I RECEIVED A CALL FROM TEXAS GENERAL LAND OFFICE NEEDING TO CONFIRM INFORMATION. NOTIFIED CAPT. LAMIER OF POHA FORE DEPARTMENT AND REQUESTED THEIR ASSISTANCE. POHA FIRE DEPARTMENT, HULCHER SHELBY STARTZ, AND MYSELF MET AT 5:30 TO FINALIZE PLANS WHEN BOARDING VESSEL. PORT POLICE OFFICER MOON WAS ON SCENE. WE BOARDED THE VESSEL APPRX. 7:45A.M., HULCHER TOOK A AIR SAMPLE. VESSEL BEGAN WORK AT 0700 HRS BEHIND THE HOUSE. WE BEGAN MAKING A DIAPER ON THE BACK OF THE CONTAINER SO IT COULD BE LIFTED OFF THE VESSEL AND DRAYED TO ISOLATED AREA. ALSO IN ATTENDANCE WAS THE SCHIRM REPRESENTATIVES AND TWO USCG OFFICERS. THE CONTAINER HAD APPRX 5 DRIPS PER MINUTE. THE DIAPER HELD AND CONTAINER WAS REMOVED. TO LIGHT POLE 32 ISOLATED AREA. HULCHER HAD CLEANUP CREW ON BOARD THE VESSEL NEUTRALIZING, DECONNING CONTAMINATED AREA. THEY COMPLETED CLEAN UP ON SHIP APPRX 10:30A.M. PORT FIRE DEPARTMENT, USCG JOSEPHN PLASECIA AND MUSELF ESCORTED CONTAINER TO ISOLATED AREA. HULCHER SPREAD PLASTIC ON THE GROUND AND WE BACKED THE CONTAINER UP ON THE PLASTIC, THEN DRAPPED IT OVER THE CEMENT DOCK. THE CONTAINER NEVER DRIPPED ANY PRODUCT. THE SEAL WAS BROKEN. IT WAS NOT APPARENT WHERE THE LEAK WAS COMING FROM. THE ENTIRE FLOOR WAS SOAKED FROM THE NOSE TO FRONT OF CONTAINER. MORE PLASTIC WAS PUT DOWN AND A DECON AREA SET

column168: TRAIN Q30219 WAS STOPPED ABOUT 5 MILES OUTSIDE OF CSX TRANSPORTATION'S RAIL YARD IN SOUTH CHARLESTON, WV ACCOUNT OF A REPORT THAT A CAR IN THE TRAIN WAS LEAKING.  THE CREW INSPECTED THE TRAIN AND FOUND NYC889656, LOAD AMMONIUM NITRATE, WAS LEAKING FROM ONE OF THE BOTTOM UNLOADING SLIDE GATES. THE CAR WAS PULLED INTO THE SOUTH CHARLESTON YARD WHERE CSXT'S MECHANICAL PERSONNEL SUCCEEDED IN STOPPING THE LEAK BY PLACING WOODEN WEDGES IN THE SLIDE GATE.  ACCORDING TO THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT, THE LEAK WAS CAUSED BY METAL CORROSION AT THE CORNER  OF THE A END BOTTOM SLIDE GATE.  THE SLIDE GATE WAS CLOSED TIGHT AND WAS SEALED.  PCS SALES, THE SHIPPER, WAS NOTIFIED VIA CHEMTREC.  THE CAR WAS MOVED INTO THE TRANSFLO FACILITY FOR UNLOADING. CSXT'S HAZARDOUS MATERIALS DEPARTMENT RESPONDED AN EMERGENCY RESPONSE CONTRACTOR TO CHECK THE TRACK AND CLEANUP ANY SPILLED PRODUCT.  THE CONTRACTOR RECOVERED APPROXIMATELY 400 POUNDS OF PRODUCT THAT THEY WILL PROCESS FOR BENEFICIAL REUSE.

column168: THE DRIVER HAD LOADED HIS FINAL LOAD AT THE IMC SOUTH PIERCE FACILITY AND WAS EN-ROUTE TO IMC NEW WALES FACILITY. THE DRIVER FAILED TO CLOSE A 2-INCH BLEEDER VALVE USED TO BLOW DOWN THE TRAILER AFTER UNLOADING. THE EXITED THE LOADING AREA AND PROCEEDED TO SCALE OUT AND COLLECT HIS PAPERWORK. THE DRIVER EXITED THE PLANT FACILITY EN-ROUTE TO IMC NEW WALES FACILITY. WHEN THE DRIVER APPROACHED THE STOP SIGN AT THE END OF THE ENTRANCE ROAD LEADING INTO THE PLANT FACILITY THE SURGE IN THE TANKER CAUSED PRODUCT TO BE FORCED OUT OF THE 2-INCH BLEEDER VALVE. THE DRIVER CONTINUED TO HIS DESTINATION, AS HE WAS NOT AWARE HE HAD DISCHARGED PRODUCT FROM THE VENTING SYSTEM ON THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER ARRIVED AT THE NEW WALES FACILITY UNAWARE THAT HE DISCHARGED APPROXIMATELY 150 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID ON THE HIGHWAY. 150 GALLONS OF SULFURIC ACID WAS RELEASED ON IMPERVIOUS SURFACE (ASPHALT). THERE WERE NO INJURIES TO THE GENERAL PUBLIC OR ANY OF CTL EMPLOYEES. NOTIFICATION WAS MADE TO THE EPA. REPORT TAKEN BY TIM RICE @ 813-744-6462 FOLLOW-UP REPORT WITH THE EPA ATLANTA,GA OFFICE @ 404-562-8705 UPDATE INFORMATION WITH JEROLD FUSION. TIM ODELL FROM ENVIRONMENTAL SPECIALTY SERVICE HANDLED THE SITE PLAN AND HAS PERFORMED THE REQUIRED TEST AND WILL FILE THE REQUIRED REPORTS. IMMEDIATE ACTION: CTL SENT A CLEAN UP CREW OUT TO SPREAD LIME AND SODA ASH TO NEUTRALIZE THE AFFECTED AREAS. THE DRIVER IN QUESTION WAS INSTRUCTED TO RETURN TO THE MULBERRY TERMINAL FOR MAINTENANCE TO INSPECT THE EQUIPMENT AFTER THE LOAD WAS UNLOADED. IN THE INITIAL INSPECTION OF THE EQUIPMENT IT WAS FOUND THAT THE BRAKE-INTERLOCK HAD BEEN TAMPERED WITH. THE EXHAUST PORT OF THE AIR DISCHARGE HAD BEEN BLOCKED OFF. HAD THE BRAKE INTER-LOCK BEEN FUNCTIONING PROPERLY THE DRIVER WOULD NOT HAVE BEEN ABLE TO RELEASE THE BRAKES UNTIL THE BLEEDER VALVE IS IN THE CLOSED POSITION. CORRECTIVE ACTION: ALL UNIT EQUIPPED WITH A BRAKE-INTERLOCK SYSTEM HAVE BEEN INSPECTED FOR TAMPERING AND PROPER WORKING CONDITION. ADDITIONAL MEASURES HAVE BEEN TAKEN TO PREVENT TAMPERING AND MODIFICATIONS HAVE BEEN MADE TO MINIMIZE THE ABILITY FOR SOMEONE TO ALTER THE BRAKE INTER-LOCK MECHANISM. SAFETY BULLETINS HAVE BEEN DISTRIBUTED TO ALL SULFURIC ACID DRIVERS.  TERMINAL MANAGERS IN EACH LOCATION  HAVE PERSONALLY ADDRESSED THIS INCIDENT WITH EACH DRIVER. IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE DRIVER HAD KNOWLEDGE THAT THE BRAKE INTER-LOCK MECHANISM WAS NOT WORKING PROPERLY. THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED OVER THIS INCIDENT DUE TO THE SEVERITY AND THE FAILURE TO PROPERLY INSPECT HIS EQUIPMENT FOR DEFECTS.

THE DRIVER HAD FINISHED LOADING AND WAS EN-ROUTE TO HIS DESTINATION AND DISCOVER A DAMP AREA ON THE REAR OF THE TRAILER.  IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE BLEEDER VALVE WAS PARTIALLY OPEN.  A VERY SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT WAS RELEASED AND IT APPEARS THAT IT WAS CONTAINED TO THE TOP AND SIDES OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER WAS GIVEN INSTRUCTION ON PROPER SECUREMENT.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Corrosion - Exterior
column168: CARGO TANK WAS PREPARED FOR UNLOADING 5,000 GALLONS OF HYDROCHLORIC ACID INTO AN ABOVE GROUND STORAGE TANK BY PRESSURIZING CARGO TANK WITH AIR. WHEN VALVES WERE OPENED AND AIR PRESSURE APPLIED, HYDROCHLORIC ACID BEGAN LEAKING FROM MAIN PRODUCT DISCHARGE VALVE ON TOP OF CARGO TANK.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CUT OFF AIR SUPPLY, NOTIFIED CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL AND WAITED FOR LEAK TO STOP.  CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL WASHED SPILLED ACID INTO ON-SITE WASTEWATER COLLECTION SYSTEM FOR PRE-TREATMENT.  DRIVER SECURED VEHICLE AND WAITED FOR CARRIER PERSONNEL TO ARRIVE AND PREPLACE DEFECTIVE VALVE. REPAIRS COMPLETED, DRIVER FINISHED DELIVERY SUCCESSFULLY.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION, THE DEFECTIVE VALVE WAS CLEANED AND DISASSEMBLED TO DETERMINE CAUSE OF FAILURE.  FINDINGS: (1) A RUPTURE DISC FRAGMENT FROM A PREVIOUS FAILURE REMAINED IN THE TANK AND WAS EVENTUALLY DRAWN THROUGH THE PIPING TO THE VALVE SEAT.  WHEN VALVE WAS CLOSED ON A PREVIOUS DELIVERY, THE DISC FRAGMENT CUT INTO THE LINING OF THE VALVE.  HYDROCHLORIC ACID WAS IN DIRECT CONTACT WITH STEEL VALVE, WHICH CORRODED A ONE-EIGHT INCH HOLE IN THE VALVE BODY WHERE THE ACID LEAKED OUT.  (2) LINING MATERIAL OF THIS ITT GRINNEL VALVE WAS BLACK BUTYL, WHICH IS NOT ABRASIVE RESISTANT.  CORRECTIVE ACTION: INSPECT ALL LINED TRAILER VALVES TO DETERMINE LINING MATERIAL OF THE VALVES, IF NOT ABRASIVE RESISTANT, REPLACE VALVES.

column168: OIL TRANSPORT DRIVER ARRIVED AT SAM'S CLUB WITH 8800 GALLONS OF REGULAR UNLEADED GASOLINE.  THERE ARE TWO UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANKS FOR UNLEADED GASOLINE EACH WITH CAPACITY OF 20,000 GALLONS.  ULLAGE FROM TLM INVENTORY STATUS REPORT INDICATED TANK 1 WOULD HOLD 8869 GALLONS AND TANK 2 WOULD HOLD 5398 GALLONS.  DRIVER HAD ONLY ONE UNLOADING HOSE THAT PROCEEDED TO UNLOAD ABOUT 7000 GALLONS INTO TANK #1.  SOMEHOW WHILE UNLOADING INTO TANK #1 UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK #2 WAS PRESSURIZED (AIR ON TOP OF PRODUCT) WHEN DRIVER ATTEMPTED TO CHANGE UNLOADING FROM #1 INTO TANK #2 AND REMOVED THE UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK FILL CAP, GASOLINE SPRAYED INTO THE AIR UNDER PRESSURE.  THERE WAS NO PRODUCT FLOWING FROM THE DELIVERY VEHICLE AT TIME OF SPILL.  ALL INDICATIONS ARE THAT TANK #1 FILLED COMPLETELY UP, THAT THE BALL VALVE IN THE FULL PIPE FAILED TO FUNCTION AND SHUT OFF FLOW OF PRODUCT WHICH WAS FORCED THROUGH A SMALL CONNECTOR PIPE INTO TANK #2, THEREBY CAUSING A PRESSURE BUILD UP INSIDE THE TANK.  THERE WERE NO PROBLEMS WITH THE OIL TRANSPORT DELIVERY VEHICLE OR DELIVERY EQUIPMENT.

column62: Rollover Accident; Impact with Sharp or Protruding Object (e.g., nails); Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: THE VEHICLE CONFIGURATION WAS A CONVENTIONAL TRACTOR, A MAIN TRAILER AND A PUP TRAILER.  THE PUP TRAILER IS THE ONE THAT ROLLED OVER.  THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE TRACTOR OR THE MAIN TRAILER AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  OUR DRIVER WAS MAKING A RIGHT TURN FROM THE COUNTY ROAD INTO THE WESTERN GAS RESOURCES PLANT AT HILIGHT.  IT IS A SHARP RIGHT HAND TURN.  THE ROADWAY WAS ICY.  THE WEATHER WAS CLEAR AND DARK.  AS OUR DRIVER STARTED HIS TURN TO THE RIGHT THE RIGHT REAR BRAKE LOCKED UP ON THE PUP TRAILER, DRAGGING IT SIDEWAYS INTO THE BORROW DITCH WHERE IT ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE. WHEN THE PUP TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS SIDE A PROTRUSION ON THE TONGUE PUNCTURED THE HEAD OF THE CARGO TANK, CAUSING PRODUCT TO LEAK.  THE CAMPBELL COUNTY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS CALLED AND RESPONDED TO THE SCENE. THEY PLUGGED THE LEAK WITH A WOODEN PLUG AND PUTTY-LIKE MATERIAL.  A WRECKER FROM GILLETTE WY SET THE TRAILER BACK ONTO ITS WHEELS AND IT WAS TOWED AWAY STILL COUPLED TO THE MAIN TRAILER.  THE AREA WHERE THE BUTANE LEAKED WAS FROZEN AND THE PRODUCT LAY ON TOP OF THE GROUND AND EVAPORATED. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO WYOMING DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY AND IT WAS DEEMED NO FOLLOW-UP WOULD BE NECESSARY.

column168: THIS SITE ASSESSMENT INVESTIGATED A REPORTED SPILL OF GASOLINE FROM OVERFILLING AN ABOVE-GROUND STORAGE TANK (AST) AT THE THATCHER UNIFIED SCHOOL DISTRICT (TUSD) - BUS YARD.  THE WORK WAS CONDUCTED ON DECEMBER 22, 2003 BY BECK ENVIRONMENTAL AND REMEDIATION, LTD. UNDER THE ARIZONA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY'S 2002 GUIDANCE (UNDERGROUND STORAGE TANK RELEASE REPORTING AND CORRECTIVE ACTIONS).  THE SPILL OCCURRED ON THE SOUTH SIDE OF THE TUSD BUS YARD, WHERE THERE ARE TWO, 2,000 GALLON, ASTS (DIESEL AND GASOLINE), USED TO FUEL THE TUSD VEHICLES.  AN ESTIMATED SPILL OF APPROXIMATELY 130 TO 140 GALLONS OF GASOLINE OCCURRED ON NOVEMBER 7, 2003 DURING THE DELIVERY OF UNLEADED (NON-OXYGENATED) GASOLINE TO THE TUSD 2,000 GALLON DOUBLE-WALLED, STEEL, AST.  GASOLINE WAS REPORTED TO HAVE OVERFLOWED THE TANK FILL OPENING AND SPRAYED OUT OF THE VENT PIPE.  THE VENT PIPE ON THE AST WAS AT THE SAME ELEVATION AS THE FILL OPENING.  THE APPARENT IMPACTED GROUND SURFACE (GRAVEL COVER) WAS UP TO 12 FEET AWAY. THE FOLLOWING DAY (NOVEMBER 8, 2003), CKC OF SAFFORD, ARIZONA EXCAVATED THE SOILS FROM AROUND THE AST TO A DEPTH OF APPROXIMATELY 1.2 FEET AND PLACED THE EXCAVATED SOILS ON PLASTIC FOR LATER DISPOSAL.  TO ALLOW FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION AND CLEAN-UP, THE ASTS WERE MOVED.  THE EXCAVATED AREA WAS THEN COVERED WITH PLASTIC.  ON DECEMBER 22, 2003, A SITE ASSESSMENT WAS CONDUCTED THAT INCLUDED:  SURFACE SOIL GAS SURVEY, DRILLING AND SAMPLING OF THREE SOIL BORINGS AND ON SITE ANALYSIS OF THE COLLECTED SOIL SAMPLES FOR PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS WITH A STATE-CERTIFIED MOBILE LABORATORY.  THE IMPACTED SOILS MAXIMUM TOTAL PETROLEUM HYDROCARBONS WERE 500 MILLIGRAMS PER KILOGRAM (MG/KG) WITH 0.26 MG/KG BENZENE.  THESE DETECTIONS ARE BELOW THE ADEQ SOIL REMEDIATION LEVELS.  THE SOIL GAS SURVEY FOUND THAT THE APPARENT IMPACTED SOILS WERE MAINLY WITHIN THE FOOT PRINT OF THE GASOLINE AST.  THE SOIL BORINGS WITH THE ASSOCIATED SOIL ANALYSES FOUND THAT THE SOILS WERE NOT IMPACTED BELOW A DEPTH TWO FEET.  THE TOTAL AMOUNT OF GASOLINE RELEASED TO THE SOILS WAS LESS THAN 40 GALLONS.  INSPECTION OF THE AST FOUND AT LEAST 80 GALLONS OF GASOLINE STILL WITHIN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE AST.  THUS, FROM THE AMOUNT GASOLINE FOUND IN THE SECONDARY CONTAINMENT OF THE AST AND THE AMOUNT REPORTED SPILLED, MOST OF THE SPILLED GASOLINE HAS BEEN ACCOUNTED FOR.  THE REMAINING IMPACTED SOIL AREA WAS DELINEATED FOR REMOVAL AND DISPOSAL WITH THE SOILS EXCAVATED BY CKC.  NO FURTHER WORK WOULD APPEAR TO BE REQUIRED.

column168: ON FRIDAY, NOVEMBER 7TH @ 1725 HRS. ONE OF OUR WAREHOUSE AGENTS, MR. JEFF SUKONIG, REPORTED THAT HE SLIPPED AND FELL IN THE DANGEROUS GOODS STAGING AREA.  HE SAID THAT HE SLIPPED IN SOMETHING LEAKING AND THAT HIS CLOTHES WERE SPLASHED WITH THE LIQUID.  UPON INVESTIGATION, IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE LIQUID HE SLIPPED IN WAS UN3265, "CORROSIVE LIQUID, ACIDIC, ORGANIC, N.O.S. (ISOPHTHALIC ACID).  I IMMEDIATELY CALLED THE FIRE DEPARTMENT HAZARDOUS MATERIALS TEAM, WHO ALSO SEND OVER THE PARAMEDICS.  AFTER A QUICK MEDICAL EVALUATION, HE WAS RELEASED TO GO HOME AND SHOWER, FOR THE LIQUID WAS OF A VERY MINOR RISK.  I PHONED THE 24 HR EMERGENCY NUMBER ON THE DANGEROUS GOODS CERTIFICATE, AND THEY SENT ME THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET, WHICH  CONFIRMED THE LOW HAZARD OF THE LIQUID.  SINCE THIS LEAK OCCURRED IN THE LUFTHANSA CARGO WAREHOUSE, I NOTIFIED THE DUTY CARGO MANAGER ON SHIFT, MR. JOE HIRAGA.  I ALSO CALLED:  1) THE DEPARTMENT OF AIRPORTS 2) ACTION FREIGHT, THE FREIGHT FORWARDERS WHO TENDERED THIS CARGO TO LUFTHANSA FOR CARRIAGE TO DUBAI. 3) ADVANCED CLEAN-UP TECHNOLOGIES, TO CONTAIN AND REMOVE THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS USED TO "MOP-UP" THE SPILL. 4) FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION, TO REPORT THE INCIDENT.  I NOTIFIED MY OWN CARGO DEPARTMENT HEAD IN AUCKLAND, NEW ZEALAND (VIA E-MAIL).  FINALLY, I CALLED THE ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTIONS AGENCY TO OBTAIN A TEMPORARY EPA ID # (CAC 002 571 806) SO THAT THE REMOVAL AGENCY CAN DISPOSE OF THIS MATERIAL LEGALLY.  I ATTACH A FEW BLACK AND WHITE PHOTOS I TOOK AFTER THE LEAK WAS REPORTED.  I DO NOT WISH TO RENDER AN OPINION AS TO THE CAUSE OF THE BARREL FAILURE.

column62: Rollover Accident; Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 6:30 AM ON 11-13-03 A TRAILER TOWED BY OUR WESTBOUND TRUCK ROLLED OVER IN THE RIGHT SIDE DITCH AT APPROXIMATELY MILE 108.5 ON US HIGHWAY 12, APPROXIMATELY 7 MILES EAST OF LOWELL, IDAHO COUNTY, IDAHO. OUR DRIVER (JON JONES) REPORTED HE WAS RUN OFF THE ROAD BY ANOTHER EASTBOUND TRUCK APPROACHING IN HIS LANE.  HE SAID IT LOOKED LIKE A SWIFT TRUCK.  THE OTHER TRUCK DID NOT STOP,  AND WE HAVE BEEN UNABLE TO IDENTIFY THE TRUCK. OUR DRIVER HAS BEEN EMPLOYED BY US ABOUT 15 YEARS AND HAD AN EXCELLENT SAFETY RECORD.  TWO OTHER TANKER DRIVERS OF OUR ACQUAINTANCE REPORT THAT THEY HAD TALKED TO HIM ON THE CB RADIO ABOUT 2 MILES BEFORE THE ACCIDENT, AND HE WAS AWAKE AND ALERT.  WE HAVE NO REASON TO DOUBT OUR DRIVER'S STORY. THE HIGHWAY IS HEAVILY USED BY SWIFT TRANSPORTATION, AND THERE WERE 2 SEPARATE JACKKNIFE INCIDENTS INVOLVING SWIFT TRUCKS IN THAT AREA ON THE SAME DAY.  THE IDAHO STATE PATROL HAS FOUND NO EVIDENCE OF NEGLIGENCE ON OUR PART, AND NO CITATIONS WERE ISSUED.  OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO KEEP THE TOWING UNIT UPRIGHT, AND THERE WERE NO INJURIES, HOWEVER OUR 1979 FRUEHAUF 4 AXLE PULL TRAILER ROLLED IN THE DITCH AND WAS TORN OPEN BY ROCKS.  THE ENTIRE CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER (4200 GALLONS OF DYED #2 LOW-SULFUR DIESEL AND 2100 GALLONS OF CLEAR LOW-SULFUR DIESEL) WAS DISCHARGED INTO THE DITCH. BECAUSE OF EXTREMELY POROUS SOIL CONDITIONS, THE FUEL SEEPED UNDER THE ROAD, AND BEGAN TO SEEP INTO THE LOCHSA RIVER.  A HAZMAT TEAM, CONSISTING MAINLY OF THE LEWISTON IDAHO FIRE DEPT, WAS QUICKLY ON THE SEEN AND WAS ABLE TO DEPLOY CONTAINMENT BOOMS BEFORE ANY SIGNIFICANT PRODUCT ESCAPED DOWNSTREAM.  THE IDAHO DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY REPORTS THERE IS NO DANGER TO DRINKING WATER OR FISHERIES.  WE REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO THE US DOT BY PHONE THE SAME DAY.  (REPORT # 705246).  WE DISPATCHED CLEARWATER ENVIRONMENTAL AND MAXIM TECHNOLOGIES TO THE SITE.  MAXIM TECHNOLOGIES IS NOW OUR CONTRACTOR FOR MANAGING THE CLEANUP AND IS WORKING WITH MULTIPLE IDAHO AND US AUTHORITIES IN ON-GOING CLEANUP ACTIVITIES.  TO DATE ABOUT 5500 YARDS OF MATERIAL HAS BEEN REMOVED, AND WE ESTIMATE ABOUT 3 MORE WEEKS UNTIL COMPLETION. column168: ON NOVEMBER 5,2003 RMCAT ENVIRONMENTAL (RMCAT) WAS RETAINED BY EAGLE CONSTRUCTION & ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES, INC. (EAGLE) TO RESPOND TO A TRANSPORTATION INCIDENT AT THE ABOVE MENTIONED LOCATION. UPON ARRIVAL AT THE SITE, AT APPROXIMATELY 22:55 HRS, MARK CHURCHILL, EMERGENCY RESPONSE MANAGER FOR RMCAT, MET WITH AUTHORITIES FROM COLORADO DEPARTMENT OF TRANSPORTATION (CDOT), JULESBERG FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE COLORADO STATE PATROL (CSP). CSP HAZMAT TECHNICIANS BOB OWENS AND GORDON GOLDSMITH HAD PERFORMED AN ENTRY INTO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER IN SUPPLIED AIR RESPIRATORS TO ASSESS THE DAMAGE AND THE AMOUNT AND TYPE OF WASTE LEAKAGE THAT HAD OCCURRED. THIS INITIAL ASSESSMENT HAD DETERMINED THAT THERE WERE A NUMBER OF DISTRESSED AND DISTORTED DRUMS FROM THE RESULT OF THE IMPACT OF THE ACCIDENT. SPILT WASTE IN THE TRAILER EXHIBITED A PH IN THE NEUTRAL RANGE WITH AN ESTIMATED AMOUNT OF SPILLAGE AT 10-20 GALLONS. AIR MONITORING INSIDE THE TRAILER INDICATED AN LEL BELOW 10% WITH THE OXYGEN LEVEL IN THE ACCEPTABLE RANGE FOR WORK IN THE TRAILER WITH AIR PURIFYING RESPIRATORS. IT WAS DECIDED BASED ON THE PRELIMINARY INFORMATION GATHERED THAT AIR MONITORING WOULD BE PERFORMED AROUND THE OUTSIDE OF THE TRAILER TO ENSURE NO HAZARDOUS CONDITION EXITED THAT WOULD PRECLUDE RE-OPENING WESTBOUND I-76. RMCAT THEN PERFORMED AIR MONITORING INSIDE AND OUTSIDE THE TRAILER. READINGS OUTSIDE THE TRAILER INDICATED NO ORGANIC VAPORS PRESENT AS MEASURED WITH A PID, AND NO LEL, CO, H2S, OR OXYGEN DEPLETION DETECTIONS INSIDE THE TRAILER, LEL, CO, O2 AND H2S LEVELS WERE NORMAL, WITH PID READING RANGING FROM 13-250 PPM UPON CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE CARGO, IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE ELEVATED PID READING WERE DUE TO A BREACHED DRUM OF WASTE ACETONE WHICH HAD NOT SPILLED BUT WAS OPEN TO THE AIR, A TRANSFER TRACTOR-TRAILER WAS CONTRACTED THROUGH CLEAN HARBORS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES (CHES), KIMBALL NE. FOR OFFLOADING OF THE DRUMS FROM THE DAMAGED TRAILER FOR TRANSPORT TO THE RMCAT FACILITY IN DENVER. SINCE THE DAMAGED TRAILER WAS PARKED IN THE MEDIAN AND SOME OF THE DRUMS WOULD REQUIRE OVERPACKING, AND RMCAT TRUCK WAS POSITIONED AS AN INTERMEDIATE STAGING AREA AT THE REAR OF THE DAMAGED TRAILER FOR INSPECTION, CLEANING RELABELING, AND OVERPACKING OF THE DRUMS WITH A FORKLIFT BEFORE THEY WERE LOADED INTO THE CHES TRAILER. THE CARGO OF THE TRAILER CONSISTED OF VARIOUS TYPE ON NON-HAZARDOUS WASTE INCLUDING PALLETS OF TONER CARTRIDGES AND DRUM OF LIQUID WASTE, AND RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTES INCLUDING WASTE ACETONE, NITRIC ACID SOLUTIONS, FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS AND CORROSIVE LIQUIDS, AMONG OTHERS. IN TOTAL, NINETY-NINE DRUMS AND FIVE PALLETS OF TONER CARTRIDGES WERE TRANSPORTED ON THE SAVANNAH TRANSPORT TRAILER, TWO DRUMS LISTED ON MANIFEST #45281, GENERATED BY CHROMALLOY OF CARSON CITY, NV AS NON-RCRA HAZARDOUS WASTE, LIQUID (EVAPORATOR SLUDGE), WERE IDENTIFIED AS THE DRUMS WHICH HAD SPILLED THEIR CONTENTS INSIDE THE TRAILER. TOTAL ESTIMATED AMOUNT OF THE SPILLAGE WAS 10-20 GALLONS. NO LIQUID SPILLED

THE TANKCAR WAS MOVED TO THE WEST END RIP TRACK FOR STORAGE.  ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED.  JOHN JACKSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY ADVISED THAT THE MANWAY GASKET WAS MISALIGNED AND DEFECTIVE.  THE GASKET WAS REPLACED WITH A ONE TIME SEAL GORE-TEX GASKET.  THE TANK CAR WAS RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.  ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.

WHILE INSPECTING RESIDUE TANK CAR ACFX 72447, LOCATED ON BOWL TRACK 2 ENGLEWOOD YARD, MGR LERCH NOTED VAPOR LEAKING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE. MGR LERCH CONTACTED THE LOAD SHIPPER, TAUBER OIL AND SPOKE TO TRANSPORTATION MGR LORY TAUBER.  UPON ADVISING HER OF THE STATUS OF THE CAR, ARRANGEMENTS WERE MADE FOR AMERICAN RAILCAR INDUSTRIES MOBIL REPAIR TO RESPOND AND REPAIR THE VALVE.  ARI PERSONNEL REPLACED THE O-RINGS IN THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE, WHICH SECURED THE CAR FROM ANY FURTHER RELEASE.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column62: Loose Closure, Component, or Device; Defective Component or Device
column168: JOHN VALLEY, MANAGER YARD OPERATIONS, REPORTED TANKCAR GATX 91164, LOCATED NEAR THE KRESS BUILDING IN THE LIVONIA, LOUISIANA RAIL YARD WAS VENTING. NO SPILLS WERE OBSERVED AND NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED.  THOMAS ROBINSON, MANAGER ENVIRONMENTAL FIELD OPERATIONS, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  ALL NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.  MANAGER ROBINSON DETERMINED THAT THE A END LIQUID VALVE WAS LOOSE AND CONSEQUENTLY TIGHTENED IT DOWN AND LOOSENED THE PLUG IN THE THROAT OF THE VALVE TO CONFIRM THE LEAK WAS SEALED.  MR. ROBINSON ADVISED THAT A SMALL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT DRIPPED OUT BUT VAPORIZED BEFORE REACHING THE GROUND.  MGR. ROBINSON ADVISED THE LEAK ON THE A END OF THE TANKCAR WAS PROPERLY SECURED AND A SMALL LEAK WAS ALSO LOCATED FROM THE LIQUID VALVE ON THE B END OF THE TANKCAR AND SECURED.  MR. ROBINSON FURTHER ADVISED THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING SEAL 143524 WAS REMOVED TO MAKE REPAIRS AND THEN REPLACED WITH SEAL UPRREMG001533.  IN ADDITION, MR. ROBINSON ADVISED THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED VIA CELL PHONE, BUT DID NOT RESPOND.

D A WILLIAMS, TRAIN CREW, REPORTED A LEAK FROM TANKCAR GATX 61133, ENTRAINED ON THE MWCRO 15, LOCATED IN MILFORD, UT.  MR. WILLIAMS ADVISED THE CREW HAD OBSERVED SEVERAL SMALL STREAKS OF THE PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF THE TANKCAR.  LEON HENDRICKSON, MANAGER OF CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION, AND ROBERT BAVIER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY WERE BOTH NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  THE TANK CAR SHOWED SIGNS OF A PAST RELEASE, BUT NO EVIDENCE OF MOISTURE OR A CURRENT RELEASE.  INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR DETERMINED THAT THE RUPTURE DISK HAD FAILED.  THE DISK WAS REPLACED IN KIND AND THE TANK CAR DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED TO TRANSPORTATION.  NECESSARY NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE.

column25: B P WEST COAST PRODUCTS LLC
column168: WHILE PERFORMING RANDOM TANK CAR INSPECTIONS AT 18TH STREET YARD IN KANSAS CITY, KS, LANE SEKAVEC, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY DISCOVERED TWO TANK CARS LEAKING VAPOR.  ADMX 30593 WAS DISCOVERED TO BE DISCHARGING VAPOR FROM A DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  ADMX 29262 WAS LEAKING VAPOR FROM A DEFECTIVE SAMPLE PORT CAP.  JOHN MARTIN WITH ADM WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE DEFECTS.  MR. SEKAVEC REPAIRED ADMX 29262 BY REMOVING THE CAP AND REINSTALLING IT SO THAT NO VAPOR WAS ESCAPING, SECURING THE CAR FOR TRANSPORTATION.  ADMX 30593 WAS REPAIRED BY REMOVING THE DEFECTIVE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE AND REPLACING IT WITH A PLUG PROVIDED BY ADM.  A ONE-TIME MOVEMENT AUTHORITY WAS OBTAINED FROM THE FRA FOR ADMX 30593 TO ALLOW IT TO MOVE TO A REPAIR FACILITY FOR REQUALIFICATION.

column42: AEROSOLS, POISON, PACKING GROUP III (EACH NOT EXCEEDING 1 L CAPACITY)
column62: Defective Component or Device; Improper Preparation for Transportation; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: ICTF SECURITY REPORTED A LEAKING HAZARDOUS CONTAINER, TRLU 586119, AT YELLOW 206 IN THE ICTF, LONG BEACH, CA DEAN COOPER, MANAGER CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED. MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE CONTENTS AND FOUND THE LADING IN SMALL BOXES, HAND STACKED FROM THE REAR DOOR. THE BOXES WERE STAIR STEPPED UP FROM THE REAR DOOR AND NO BLOCKING OR BRACING TO SECURE THE CARTONS. DURING TRANSIT, THE CARTONS SHIFTED TOWARDS THE REAR DOORS AND WERE LEANING AT A 45 DEGREE ANGLE. ALL THE VIABLE CARTONS WERE WET FROM THE PRODUCT BEING RELEASED. THE CONTAINER WAS MOVED TO THE CUSTOMS DOCK WHERE IT COULD BE CONTAINED AND INSPECTED IN DETAIL. THE CARTON CONTAINED SELECT HAIR MOUSSE IN FOUR OUNCE AEROSOL CYLINDERS, PACKAGED SIX TO A CARTON. IT WAS SUSPECTED THE CYLINDERS HAD BEEN ACTIVATED FROM THE WEIGHT OF THE CARTONS SHIFTING. CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE INDIVIDUAL CYLINDERS NOTED FAILURE AT THE SIDE SEAM AND BOTTOM CHIME OF THE CYLINDERS. IT WAS NOTED THE CARTONS WERE ONLY MARKED WITH THE FLAMMABLE LABEL, WITH NO HAZARD CLASS (2). THE CARTONS WERE ALSO MARKED AEROSOLS UN1952. THE INDIVIDUAL CYLINDERS HAD NO SPECIFICATION MARKINGS. ALL OF THE WET CARTONS WERE HAND REMOVED FROM THE CONTAINER. THE INDIVIDUAL CYLINDERS WERE REMOVE FROM ORIGINAL CARTONS AND PLACED INTO TRI-WALL BOXES FOR CONTAINMENT. APPROXIMATELY 3600 CYLINDERS WERE BOXED AND MOVED TO ANOTHER CONTAINER, APHU 453243, FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE. THE REMAINING HAIR CARE PRODUCTS THAT WERE NOT AFFECTED, REMAINED IN THE ORIGINAL CONTAINER PENDING DISPOSITION. OUTCOME PENDING FRA INVESTIGATION.

CLOSER INSPECTION OF THE INDIVIDUAL CYLINDERS NOTED FAILURE AT THE SIDE SEAM AN BOTTOM CHIME OF THE CYLINDERS.  IT WAS NOTED THE CARTONS WERE ONLY MARKED WITH THE FLAMMABLE LABEL, WITH NO HAZARD CLASS (2).  THE CARTONS WERE ALSO MARKED WITH AEROSOLS UN1950.  THE INDIVIDUAL CYLINDERS HAD NO SPECIFICATION MARKINGS.  ALL OF THE WET CARTONS WERE REMOVED BY HAND FROM THE CONTAINER. THE INDIVIDUAL CYLINDERS WERE MOVED FROM THE ORIGINAL CARTONS AND PLACED INTO TRI-WALL BOXES FOR CONTAINMENT.  APPROXIMATELY 3

JOHN NINE, CAR FOREMAN, COLTON, CA., REPORTED TANKCAR RPBX 23500 HAD RELEASED SOME OF ITS PRODUCT ON THE SIDE OF THE TANK.  NO GROUND OR WATERWAYS WERE AFFECTED.  NO INJURIES WERE REPORTED.  DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED.  MANAGER COOPER INSPECTED THE TANK CAR ON BOWL 3 OF THE HUMP YARD, AND NOTED A MISTING (LESS THAN ONE GALLON) OF PRODUCT ALONG THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR NEAR THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE.  THE SPRING LOADED SAFETY RELIEF VALVE IS MOUNTED ABOVE THE TOP PORTION OF THE TANK SHELL, AND HAD ACTIVATED  DURING HUMPING OPERATIONS.  THE VALVE WAS INSPECTED AND NO DEFECTS WERE NOTED, INDICATING THE CAR SUSTAINED AN OVER SPEED IMPACT, CAUSING THE VALVE TO OPERATE WITH THE GENERATED LIQUID SURGE.  THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD RESET ITSELF FOLLOWING THE RELEASE AND THERE WERE NO MECHANICAL DEFECTS NOTED TO THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE.

column168: ACCIDENT REPORT IN OCEANSIDE, CALIFORNIA (11/16/03) 1.  DATE & LOCAL TIME OF THE INCIDENT:  NOVEMBER 16, 2003, 0600 2.. PHYSICAL LOCATION OF INCIDENT:  EAST SIDE OF INTERSTATE 5 JUST NORTH OF THE HWY 78 TRANSITION   FOR WESTBOUND 78 TO NORTHBOUND I-5. 3.  NATURE  OF INCIDENT:  BENETO DRIVER WAS TRAVELING NORHTBOUND I-5 AT APPROXIMATELY 45 MILES PER  HOUR PULLING A SLIGHT GRADE.  AS HE PASSED THE TRANSITION ROAD FROM WESTBOUND 78 TO NORTHBOUND I-5 HE LOOKED IN HIS PASSENGER REAR-VIEW MIRROR AND SAW HEADLIGHTS RAPIDLY APPROACHING HIS VEHICLE (THE CAR WAS REPORTEDLY TRAVELING AT 60 TO 65 MPH).  IT WAS RAINING HEAVILY AND THE ONCOMING CAR SPUN OUT. AND HIT THE UNDERSIDE OF THE OUR SEMI-TRAILER AT THE OFFLOADING HEAD AREA.  THE CAR BOUNCED OFF AND THEN RAN INTO THE DIRT EMBANKMENT ON THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY.  THE IMPACT OF THE COLLISION DAMAGED THE PLUMBING EXITING THE INTERNAL VALVES.  COMPARTMENT 2 PLUMBING WAS NEARLY SEVERED AT THE INTERNAL; COMPARTMENT 3 PLUMBING WAS BADLY DAMAGED.  ADDITIONALLY, THE IMPACT OF THE CAR PULLED OPEN 3 OF THE INTERNAL VALVES.  THE BENETO DRIVER PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE HIGHWAY AND EXITED THE VEHICLE TO SURVEY THE DAMAGE.  PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING THE TRAILER; HE SAW THE THREE OPEN INTERNAL VALVES AND KICKED THEM CLOSED WITH HIS FOOT IMMEDIATELY REDUCING MOST OF THE PRODUCT FLOW.  AS SOME PRODUCT WAS STILL ESCAPING FROM THE #2 AND #3 INTERNALS HE YANKED AT THE INTERNAL CABLES AND FURTHER REDUCED THE FLOW.  HE PLACED BUCKETS UNDER THE LEAKING INTERNALS AND THEN CALLED 911.  HE FOLLOWED BY CALLING BENETO DISPATCH WHO IMMEDIATELY NOTIFIED BILLY BROOKS, BENETO SAN DIEGO TERMINAL MANAGER, AND BILL MYERS, GENERAL MANAGER.  THE BENETO EMERGENCY RESPONSE VEHICLE WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SITE.  THE DRIVER THEN BEGAN PLACING HIS ABSORBENT TOWELS, AND GRANULATED ABSORBENT DAMNING THE PRODUCT FLOW FROM THE STORM DRAIN SOME 50 FEET SLIGHTLY DOWNHILL FROM THE TRUCK.  THE CHP ARRIVED AND THEN THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND CALTRANS.  CALTRANS NOTIFIED THE US COAST GUARD, THE SAN DIEGO COUNTY ENVIRONMENTAL RESPONSE GROUP, AND OTHERS INCLUDING FOSS ENVIRONMENTAL.  BILLY BROOKS ARRIVED FOLLOWED BY BILL MYERS AND SHORTLY THEREAFTER BENETO'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TRAILER.  THE FLOW HAD BEEN CONTAINED TO LEAKAGE INTO THE BUCKETS.  THE BUCKETS WERE PERIODICALLY EMPTIED INTO A DRUM PROVIDED BY THE FIRE DEPARTMENT.  WE WERE COLLECTING SOME 10 TO 15 GALLONS PER HOUR.  NO OTHER PRODUCT WAS BEING LOST.  WHEN OUR BENETO PUMP TRUCK ARRIVED THE TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM THE LEAKING COMPARTMENTS WAS BEGUN.  THE FIRE DEPARTMENT AND OTHER OFFICIALS ON SITE WERE VERY COMPLIMENTARY ABOUT THE MANNER IN WHICH THE BENETO PERSONNEL WERE HANDLING THE LOSS AND PERMITTED BENETO TO HANDLE THE ENTIRE CLEANUP AND TRANSFER WITHOUT ASSISTANCE BEYOND STANDING BY IN CASE OF FIRE OR UNEXPECTED ADDITIONAL RELEASE.  THE 24-YEAR SERVICE BATTALION  COMMANDER TOLD BILL MYERS IT WAS THE BEST CLEANUP HE HAD PERFORMED BY A PRIVATE COMPANY. 4.  DAMAGE CONTROL MEASURES:  ALL NECESSARY MEASURES

column168: 11-4-04 - EMPLOYEE OF MEYERS OIL CO. INC. DELIVERED 150 GALLONS OF #2 HEAT OIL TO APARTMENT #2 LOCATED AT 218 EAST THIRD AVE, MITCHELL, SD.  TENANT FROM ANOTHER APARTMENT INFORMED MEYERS OIL EMPLOYEE, THAT STRONG ODOR WAS PRESENT.  MEYERS OIL EMPLOYEE CONTACTED OWNER OF APARTMENT THAT SOMETHING WAS WRONG.  MEYERS OIL EMPLOYEE AND OWNER ENTERED BASEMENT OF APARTMENT AND DISCOVERED THAT FILL PIPE WAS NOT CONNECTED TO FUEL TANK - FUEL TANK HAD BEEN REMOVED AND PIPE INSIDE BASEMENT HAD BEEN SAWED OFF WITH RAG, STUCK IN PIPE, TO PUG FILL PIPE.  OWNER OF APARTMENT CONTACTED FIRE DEPARTMENT, POLICE, LOCAL OEM, DENR (SD).  FIRE DEPARTMENT CHECKED BASEMENT, MANHOLES, ACCESS POINTS FOR EXPLOSIVE VAPORS.  POLICE CLOSED STREET.  EVACUATED RESIDENTS OF APARTMENT BECAUSE OF ODOR (RED CROSS HELPED).  CITY SEWER DEPT FLUSHED LINES TO MOVE FUEL THROUGH QUICKLY.  CLEANING COMPANY CALLED IMMEDIATELY TO BEGIN CLEANUP.  11-5-04 - DON MEYERS CALLED NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER TO SEE IF THIS NEEDED TO BE REPORTED (MR. WHITE)

column168: OUR DRIVER WAS DELIVERING OIL TO TANK WHICH WAS LOCATED IN BASEMENT.  THE COMPARTMENT THAT HE WAS PUMPING FROM RAN OUT.  HE WENT BACK TO THE TRUCK TO SWITCH TO A FULL SECTION.  WHEN HE WENT BACK TO THE BASEMENT HE REALIZED HE HAD LEFT THE FUEL NOZZLE OPEN.  WHEN HE SWITCHED FROM EMPTY SECTION TO A FULL ONE IT CAUSED THE NOZZLE TO COME OUT OF THE FILL  PIPE AND SPILL OIL. THE DRIVER KNOWS NOW IT IS ABSOLUTELY NECESSARY TO TURN NOZZLE OFF WHEN CHANGING SECTIONS.
